POINT FIRE CAUSE BY ESTIMATES FIRE ACREAGE

# Remove rows with non-finite values in the EstTotalAcres column
fire_clean <- fire[!is.na(fire$EstTotalAcres) & is.finite(fire$EstTotalAcres), ]

# Plot the cleaned data
ggplot(fire_clean, aes(x = GeneralCause, y = EstTotalAcres)) +
  geom_point(size=1) + 
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +  # linear regression line
  labs(x = "Cause of Fire",
       y = "EstTotalAcres",
       title = "Affected Acreage affected by causes of fire ") +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))+ 
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma, breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

BAR CHART OF FIRE CAUSE AND ESTIMATED TOTAL ACRES IN DIFFERENT COLORS

library(ggplot2)
library(RColorBrewer)

# Choose Paired ColorBrewer palette
palette <- brewer.pal(n = length(unique(fire_clean$GeneralCause)), name = "Paired")

ggplot(fire_clean, aes(x = FireYear, y = EstTotalAcres, fill = GeneralCause)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
  labs(x = "Fire Year",
       y = "Estimated Total Acres",
       title = "Estimated Total Acres by Fire Year",
       fill = "Fire Cause") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = palette) +  # Use the chosen palette for fill colors
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma, breaks = scales::pretty_breaks(n = 10))

####USE THIS TABLE OF TOTAL BURNED ACRES FROM THE TOP FIRE CAUSE OF EACH YEAR

library(dplyr)
##

##     filter, lag

# Select only the columns you need

selected_columns <- dplyr::select(fire_clean, FireYear, GeneralCause, EstTotalAcres)

# Group by FireYear and filter for the top cause of each year
top_cause_table <- selected_columns %>%
  group_by(FireYear) %>%
  top_n(1, EstTotalAcres) %>%
  arrange(FireYear)

# Print the table
print(top_cause_table)

human vs lightning caused fires

# Filter the shapefile to include only human-caused fires
lightning_fires <- fireshp[fireshp$humanorlig == "Lightning", ]

# Filter the shapefile to include only human-caused fires
human_fires <- fireshp[fireshp$humanorlig == "Human", ]

ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = human_fires, aes(fill = "Human"), color = "orange", alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data = lightning_fires, aes(fill = "Lightning"), color = "blue", alpha = 0.5) +
   geom_sf(data = orsf, fill = "NA", color = "black", size = 1) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("orange", "blue"),
                    name = "Cause of Fire",
                    labels = c("Human", "Lightning")) +
  labs(title = "Human vs Lightning-Caused Fires in Oregon") +
  theme_bw() +
  theme(axis.line = element_line(color = "black"))
